<font color="#FF0000">MOVIES</font><br>
<tt>Fri Feb 14 14:50:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ok, ok, I admit that for these many years, I have avoided viewing the films discussed on this thread.  When &quot;Deer Hunter&quot; first hit the theaters, I went to see it, or at least, part of it.  When the village scene, with the choppers, the NVA tossing the frag into the bunker with the civies came on screen, I found myself outside of the theater, hyperventilating, shaking, and soaked in a cold sweat.  I thought to myself, &quot;Why would I want to put myself through this shit!&quot;, and left.<br><br>
When &quot;Platoon&quot; hit the theater, it was the talk of the town. Everyone wanted me to go and see it.  Just the whoop-di-doo about the film, rattled my cage.<br><br>
So, I figured enough, is enough!  Over the last couple of months, I went and rented a few of the videos touted by those on this thread. Yup, fucken things rattled my cage.  I recognized things that I have long forgottened.<br><br>
My &quot;objective&quot; criticism is that not one truely reflected my time in Nam.  There were parts of each film, however, which I could relate to.<br><br>
The scene in &quot;Platoon&quot; where they were humping up a hill, thick with brush, slipping and sliding on the mud.  The terrain and much, other than the rape, village scene and all the other bullshit, I really related to.<br><br>
There were some things in &quot;84 Charlie Mopic&quot;, that I could relate to, but I found myself criticizing it more than anything else.  1. Anybody out there ever had LRRP rations instead of beans and mother-fuckers C-rations? 2. Who had time to moan, wail, scream and shout, when someone was &quot;dusted&quot;? Especially, when Charlie was around!  Don't know about you guys, but I never saw that; those in my unit waited til we got home, and then mostly years after to mourn for the dead. 3. This is only from the perspective of a medic; treating an abdominal would like a sucking chest wound and doing it ass-backwards. 4. Our RTO's didn't have the luxury of humping an external speaker for the prick-25-did they really exist in the bush? 5. When you guys were in a world of hurt, did you allow any free hands to NOT have a weapon to help?  Maybe I'm being to critical, maybe a defense mechanism to hold off the true impact of the film, I don't know. I know this, though, someone would have trashed that camera and either stuffed a '16 in his hands or elsewhere!  The one scene that really hurt, was when they all sat around the radio, listening to others and their hurt.  This, I remember.<br><br>

